eBorder\" style=\"border:0;border-width:2px;vertical-align:top;margin:0\"><img role=\"presentation\" class=\"imageDropZone mceImage\" src=\"https://mcusercontent.com/be20bbfba341582993786f7f0/images/9997c97b-a7c5-a897-d068-97310b7a690e.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"298\" height=\"auto\" style=\"display:block;max-width:298px;width:298px;height:auto\"/></span>\n<![endif]-->\n</td></tr><tr><td id=\"gutterContainerId-652\"><table><tbody><tr><td id=\"b652\"><table><tbody><tr><td><p><img src=\"https://fonts.gstatic.com/s/e/notoemoji/17.0/1f49e/72.png\" alt=\"💞\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\"> Cheers to</p><p>• <strong>Aslin Green Grass</strong> West Coast IPA</p><p>• <strong>Vasen Fox Ridge</strong> Saison</p><p>• Shop fav<strong> Von Trapp Oktoberfest</strong> is back for the season! </p></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr><tr><td id=\"b734\"><table><tbody><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr><tr><td id=\"gutterContainerId-733\"><table><tbody><tr><td id=\"b733\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Hot Crowler &amp; Growler Fills<p>Forest &amp; Main Weathervane West Coast IPA</p><p>Wild East Turnstyle Nopal Margarita Sour</p></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr><tr><td id=\"b599\"><table><tbody><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr><tr><td id=\"b579\"><!--[if !mso]><!--><table><tbody><tr><td><img src=\"https://mcusercontent.com/be20bbfba341582993786f7f0/images/c393d9a0-58e5-f9ad-737a-400b98d6cf45.jpeg\" width=\"520\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\"></td></tr></tbody></table><!--<![endif]-->\n<!--[if mso]>\n<span class=\"mceImageBorder\" style=\"border:0;border-width:2px;vertical-align:top;margin:0\"><img role=\"presentation\" class=\"imageDropZone mceImage\" src=\"https://mcusercontent.com/be20bbfba341582993786f7f0/images/c393d9a0-58e5-f9ad-737a-400b98d6cf45.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"520.1999999999999\" height=\"auto\" style=\"display:block;max-width:520.1999999999999px;width:520.1999999999999px;height:auto\"/></span>\n<![endif]-->\n</td></tr><tr><td id=\"gutterContainerId-723\"><table><tbody><tr><td id=\"b723\"><table id=\"section_e31934b4441cb26fba8847fca20905e2\"><tbody><tr><td><table><tbody><tr><td id=\"mceColumnId--37\"><table><tbody><tr><td id=\"b-22\"><table><tbody><tr><td><table><tbody><tr><td id=\"mceColumnId--47\"><table><tbody><tr><td id=\"b722\"><table><tbody><tr><td><table><tbody><tr><td id=\"mceColumnId-721\"><table><tbody><tr><td id=\"gutterContainerId-580\"><table><tbody><tr><td id=\"b580\"><table><tbody><tr><td><span>New wines in the door!</span><p><strong><span>Poggio Costa Prosecco Rose</span><span>:</span></strong><span><span><span><span>Poggio Costa means \"The Hill by the Sea\" referring to the hillside ranges along the northern Adriatic coast of Italy. If you can believe it, Prosecco Rosé is a relatively new official category only receiving its DOC designation in 2020. Delicate and dry, Glera and Pinot Nero make the perfect duo - Glera with the floral charm and Pinot Nero the color and red berry bursts. Sustainable.</span></span></span></span></p><p><strong>Colutta Pinot Grigio Ramato</strong>: <span><span><span><span>Ramato is a historic style of skin contact Pinot Grigio that has ridden the wave of orange wine back into popularity of its own. While orange wine can be made from any white grape, Ramato is specifically and only Pinot Grigio. (Fun fact, while Pinot Grigio is a \"white wine\", its grapes actually do not have a white skin - they're grayish-pink / purple!) If you're new to Ramato, Colutta is a great place to start - fresh and bright with notes of peach, apple, and citrus rind plus balanced acidity and gentle, dusty tannins.</span></span></span></span></p><p><strong>Southwest Mountain Cabernet Franc</strong>: <span><span><span><span>A chillable red Virginia Cab Franc? Absolutely. Get ready for VA Cab Franc like you've never seen it before. Crunchy red fruit and brambly dark fruit sit inside an incredibly light-on-its-feet body. Floral notes and fine tannins plus a hint of candied texture that makes an incredibly complex wine feel simple and accessible. And give that puppy a swirl and a sniff - this is one of the most intoxicating smelling wines in the shop.</span></span></span></span></p><p><strong><span><span><span><span>Mary Taylor Cotes de Gascogne Rouge</span></span></span></span></strong><span><span><span><span>: </span></span><span><span>Mary Taylor believes that wine should tell you where it's from and who made it, and that price should reflect the Old World view of wine as an everyday luxury, not a special occasion. We love Mary's philosophy and her wines. While the Côtes de Gascogne is overwhelmingly white wine country — reds make up less than 10% of production — Côtes de Gascogne Rouge is a regional red worth knowing. An unoaked blend of native but familiar varietals with dark berry fruit, lush roundness and grippy tannins. Falling in that sweet middle spot somewhere between a picnic wine and a dinner wine. Sustainable.</span></span></span></span></p></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr><tr><td id=\"b724\"><table><tbody><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr><tr><td id=\"b416\"><!--[if !mso]><!--><table><tbody><tr><td><img src=\"https://mcusercontent.com/be20bbfba341582993786f7f0/images/da7a207d-baf7-57cd-9762-3d718db4a070.jpeg\" width=\"520\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\"></td></tr></tbody></table><!--<![endif]-->\n<!--[if mso]>\n<span class=\"mceImageBorder\" style=\"border:0;border-width:2px;vertical-align:top;margin:0\"><img role=\"presentation\" class=\"imageDropZone mceImage\" src=\"https://mcusercontent.com/be20bbfba341582993786f7f0/images/da7a207d-baf7-57cd-9762-3d718db4a070.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"520.1999999999999\" height=\"auto\" style=\"display:block;max-width:520.1999999999999px;width:520.1999999999999px;height:auto\"/></span>\n<![endif]-->\n</td></tr><tr><td id=\"gutterContainerId-415\"><table><tbody><tr><td id=\"b415\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Wine we’re drinking this week:<p><strong><span><span><span><span>Pillitteri Estate Vidal Icewine</span></span></span></span></strong><span><span><span><span> is a</span></span></span><span><span><span> vibrant and welcome addition to the shop. A sip of this wine can make these hot summer days a bit sweeter and brighter. If icewine is new to you, it is produced from grapes left to naturally freeze on the vine in the coldest months of winter. This natural freeze allows for the concentration of sugars and flavors into a delightful aromatic dessert wine. When popping this dessert wine, let the aromas capture your senses with wildflower honey, stone fruit, and soft undertones of pineapple and orange peel. Whether you are eating a rich piece of chocolate cake or a charcuterie board, this icewine is surely a perfect pairing, showcasing naturally vibrant acidity and a fresh, balancing sweetness for any celebration or picnic. </span></span></span></span></p><p>.</p><p><em><span><span><span><span>This week’s writeup is brought to you by Sam B.</span></span></span></span></em></p></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr><tr><td id=\"b508\"><table><tbody><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr><tr><td id=\"gutterContainerId-452\"><table><tbody><tr><td id=\"b452\"><table id=\"section_dc64bdec645c9b64ed08458b5cbe2a12\"><tbody><tr><td><table><tbody><tr><td id=\"mceColumnId--31\"><table><tbody><tr><td id=\"b-10\"><table><tbody><tr><td><table><tbody><tr><td id=\"mceColumnId--41\"><table><tbody><tr><td id=\"b456\"><table><tbody><tr><td><table><tbody><tr><td id=\"mceColumnId-455\"><table><tbody><tr><td id=\"b453\"><!--[if !mso]><!--><table><tbody><tr><td><img src=\"https://mcusercontent.com/be20bbfba341582993786f7f0/images/8dc66e9b-7305-c0d1-5572-f12ee7415bed.jpeg\" width=\"534\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\"></td></tr></tbody></table><!--<![endif]-->\n<!--[if mso]>\n<span class=\"mceImageBorder\" style=\"border:0;border-width:2px;vertical-align:top;margin:0\"><img role=\"presentation\" class=\"imageDropZone mceImage\" src=\"https://mcusercontent.com/be20bbfba341582993786f7f0/images/8dc66e9b-7305-c0d1-5572-f12ee7415bed.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"533.8\" height=\"auto\" style=\"display:block;max-width:533.8px;width:533.8px;height:auto\"/></span>\n<![endif]-->\n</td></tr><tr><td id=\"gutterContainerId-454\"><table><tbody><tr><td id=\"b454\"><table><tbody><tr><td><p><span><span>July Tasting Events coming your way!</span></span></p></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr><tr><td id=\"b457\"><table><tbody><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr><tr><td id=\"gutterContainerId-177\"><table><tbody><tr><td id=\"b177\"><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Thanks for your business! See you soon, Beth, Julie &amp; Aidan and the entire Brew Crew</p></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table><!--[if (gte mso 9)|(IE)]></td></tr></table><![endif]--></td></tr></tbody><tbody><tr><td><!--[if (gte mso 9)|(IE)]><table align=\"center\" border=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" width=\"660\" style=\"width:660px;\"><tr><td